<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE 'SATURDAY NIGHT LIVE' CAST PROTEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Every so often, some Midwestern housewife would get all huffy about the 
questionable taste of "Saturday Night Live," and that was understandable. But 
when the cast gets all huffy. . . . 
</P>
<P>
Nora Dunn, an "SNL" regular, refused to perform because controversial comedian 
Andrew Dice Clay was host. 
</P>
<P>
Singer Sinead O'Connor withdrew as a guest. What has happened to the cast's 
sense of humor and tolerance? 
</P>
<P>
I don't recall Garrett Morris protesting when Richard Pryor hosted, even though 
Pryor used the "n" word in his act. I don't recall Jane Curtin refusing to 
appear when Eric Idle hosted, even though Idle (in drag) made fun of women in 
Monty Python skits. 
</P>
<P>
And I don't recall anybody refusing to appear when Sam Kinison -- who blazed 
the trail down which Mr. Clay now merrily skips -- hosted the show. 
</P>
<P>
"SNL" used to be on TV comedy's cutting edge. But, if cast members are going to 
get bent out of shape over things like the material of the host, then that edge 
will end up about as sharp as an installment of "Donny and Marie." 
</P>
<P>
STEVE STOLIAR, Sherman Oaks 
</P>
</TEXT>
