<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLUMBIA RIVER SURPLUS WATER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I first thought of the idea of bringing water to California from the Columbia 
River more than 40 years ago when I served as a Los Angeles City councilman. At 
that time I was given a tour of the California aqueduct by the Department of 
Water and Power. During that tour, a water engineer told me that our water 
supplies would one day be insufficient and that it was important to study new 
sources. The Columbia River, he said, was one possible source. 
</P>
<P>
Today, as we enter our fourth year of drought -- the worst in 400 years -- the 
words of that water engineer are ringing true. Water rationing has already 
started in many parts of our state and if this situation continues to worsen, 
our huge agriculture industry, upon which so many parts of this country depend, 
will be severely hit. 
</P>
<P>
The Columbia River each day dumps 90 billion gallons of fresh water into the 
Pacific Ocean. My proposal to divert just 3 billion gallons a day from that 
huge surplus, by way of aqueducts connecting the Columbia River to Shasta Lake 
and the Snake River to Lake Mead, would help to meet California's critical 
water needs without causing hardship to our neighbors in the Northwest. That 
small fraction of the Columbia's runoff would not endanger the fisheries, nor 
will it drain their water supplies. That small fraction will, however, help to 
save our agricultural regions and provide an estimated 20,000 jobs during the 
long-term construction of the aqueduct system, not just for Californians but 
for people throughout the Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
The idea of diverting surplus water from the Columbia River is not a "weird 
notion" ("Wringing Out Weird Notions," editorial, May 10), but I remember 
people saying the same thing when I wanted to place emergency telephones on the 
freeways and when I wanted firefighters trained as paramedics in Los Angeles 
County. Those ideas were considered "far-fetched" when I first proposed them, 
but they save lives and are worth every battle I fought to make them a reality. 
I have always believed that "without vision, people perish." KENNETH HAHN 
</P>
<P>
Supervisor, Second District 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles County 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
