<TEXT>
<P>
A judge found a man guilty of first-degree murder in the sulfuric acid 
poisoning of his infant son in what prosecutors said was a scheme to sue a 
commercial baby formula manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
Ricky Irby Sr., 29, could face the death penalty. Lake County Associate Judge 
Harry Hartel, who presided over a two-week, non-jury trial in Waukegan, Ill., 
set a sentencing hearing for June 29. Irby and the child's mother, Sheila 
Smith, were both charged in the death of Quinten Irby, who was 3 months old 
when he was force-fed sulfuric acid May 31, 1984. The infant lived for 27 
months at Children's Memorial Hospital in Chicago. 
