<HEADLINE>
<P>
GROUP GETS GO-AHEAD FOR ELY RECALL PETITION; 
</P>
<P>
COLLEGE DISTRICT: THE 12 SIMI AND MOORPARK RESIDENTS HAVE 160 DAYS TO GATHER 
9,900 SIGNATURES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARLOS V. LOZANO, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A citizens group that has demanded the resignation of Tom Ely, a trustee of the 
Ventura County Community College District, was given the green light Friday to 
start collecting signatures for a petition to recall him, county officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The group's petition, along with Ely's response, was approved and certified by 
the Elections Division of the county clerk's office Friday afternoon, said 
Jenny Harrison, elections services coordinator for the county. 
</P>
<P>
The citizens group last week demanded that Ely resign immediately or face the 
possibility of being recalled. The group cited "fiscal irresponsibility and 
unprofessional conduct" in regard to his "excessive travel expenses" as the 
main reason for the demand. Faculty leaders at each of Ventura County's three 
colleges have also called for Ely's resignation. 
</P>
<P>
Ely, who could not be reached for comment Friday, has said he will not resign. 
</P>
<P>
The group, made up of 12 Simi Valley and Moorpark residents, has 160 days to 
gather 15% of the signatures of the 66,000 registered voters in the 4th 
District, according to election officials. If the signatures are collected in 
time, the college Board of Trustees would be required to call a special 
election. 
</P>
<P>
Caroline Paras, an organizer of the group, said members planned to start 
collecting signatures this morning. 
</P>
<P>
For the recall to be on the November ballot, 9,900 signatures would have to be 
collected by June 15, said Ruth Schepler, director of the Elections Division. 
Otherwise, the board would not be able to call a special election until next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
Ely filed a one-page response to the recall notice with the Elections Division 
on Thursday, Schepler said. 
</P>
<P>
"You've elected me three times. I've always been prudent with your money," Ely 
wrote in his response. "For 11 years, I've been the only board member to donate 
time unselfishly, to represent you in Sacramento, Washington, D.C., or wherever 
necessary. 
</P>
<P>
"My efforts have benefited my constituents. Naturally, my expenses have been 
higher than other board members," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Ely has been the subject of controversy since it was disclosed in March that he 
had run up large gambling debts and had used his district telephone to call 
casinos in Nevada. 
</P>
<P>
A district audit of his financial records has led to a criminal investigation 
by the district attorney's office involving the possible misuse of several 
thousand dollars in district funds. 
</P>
<P>
Ely has said that the audit is flawed and that he has not violated the 
district's travel policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
