<HEADLINE>
<P>
WHO WANTS 'IDEA' PLAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mark Chalon Smith's play reviews continue to be as entertaining and insightful 
as a train wreck. A case in point is Smith's review of "Love, Sex and the IRS," 
a play produced early this year by Costa Mesa Civic Playhouse (" 'Love , Sex 
and the IRS' Makes For a Taxing Evening," Calendar, Jan. 24). 
</P>
<P>
Smith savaged the play because it was devoid of "ideas" -- still more evidence 
that Smith has no business whatsoever reviewing community theater. Any 
community theater that served its audience a steady diet of Smith's cherished 
"idea" plays would go belly-up in no time. As a longtime member of Anaheim's 
community theater, the Ana Modjeska Players, I remember -- all too well -- the 
last "idea" play we presented: "The Physicist" by Friedrich Duerrenmatt. I 
believe the play averaged five customers per performance, counting walkouts. 
</P>
<P>
Inasmuch as a major priority of community theater is to offer roles for novice 
as well as experienced local thespians, there's not much chance of staging a 
polished production of a serious, thought-provoking drama such as "Children of 
a Lesser God," which requires precision acting to be effective. "Harmless" 
comedies, as Smith calls them, provide a much better training ground for 
fledgling actors while amusing audiences that don't expect Broadway-level 
performances. 
</P>
<P>
Mr. Smith, please don't try to single-handedly change the face of community 
theater to suit your tastes. Community theater audiences want to be 
entertained, not instructed. If they want provocative drama, they'll usually 
pay a bit more and attend such theaters as South Coast Repertory, Alternative 
Repertory Theatre, Way Off Broadway Playhouse and those of local colleges and 
universities -- all of which do an excellent job of presenting "idea" plays. 
</P>
<P>
By the way, it's a good thing for the masters such as Shakespeare and Moliere, 
who occasionally wrote "harmless, non-idea" comedies, that Mark Chalon Smith 
wasn't around to put them straight. 
</P>
<P>
LEW RILEY, Yorba Linda 
</P>
</TEXT>
