479 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FREEWAYS' FUTURE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Clipboard researched by April D. Jackson / Los Angeles Times, Graphics by 
Doris Shields / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fewer than 10 county residents out of a hundred are satisfied with the freeway 
system -- the continuation of a trend that has been in place for three years. 
So widespread is this dissatisfaction that a small majority (51%) believes more 
lanes will not do the job now, that new freeways are the answer to our traffic 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
Just a few years ago, in 1982, a third of Orange Countians were satisfied with 
the freeways and only one-quarter thought we needed new ones. In any case, 
there has always been at least a two-thirds majority of the opinion that we 
need either more lanes or completely new freeways. 
</P>
<P>
Regional differences highlight the shades of opinion regarding freeways, with 
those living in the southern and western sections of the county most in favor 
of new freeways. Commuters of all stripes are convinced of the need for new 
freeways, with at least half in all groups holding that view. Perceptions as to 
what extent commuter traffic is a problem color views on this issue, but even 
those who say they have no problems making their daily run to work are ready to 
agree our freeway system is inadequate. 
</P>
<P>
AGE 
</P>
