<HEADLINE>
<P>
THREE CHEERS: 5 SCHOLARSHIPS ARE AWARDED BY HOSPITAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HERBERT J. VIDA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Scholarships of $1,000 have been awarded by the St. Joseph Hospital Foundation 
to Robert Kovacev of Yorba Linda, Derek Kelaita of Anaheim, Jason Padilla of 
Garden Grove, and Stan Kim and Quan Nguyen, both of Orange. 
</P>
<P>
Each will use the scholarship to pursue college studies in the medical and 
health care field. 
</P>
<P>
The five high school students achieved outstanding records of academic and 
extracurricular accomplishments, and each donated 200 hours as a junior 
volunteer for the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
Garden Grove resident Stacy Adair has been named the recipient of the 1990 
Dudly Boyce Outstanding Student Award as the Golden West College student who 
most exemplifies the qualities of scholarship and leadership. 
</P>
<P>
The award, which includes a $1,000 scholarship, is named after the founding 
president of the college. 
</P>
<P>
The college also named Bill Siracusa, a lifelong Huntington Beach resident, as 
its Outstanding Citizen for establishing scholarships and supporting the school 
since it opened in 1966. 
</P>
<P>
Fountain Valley resident E. Aubrey Woodroof, founder of Woodroof Laboratories 
Inc. and vice president of Winthrop Pharmaceuticals in Fountain Valley, has 
been named 1990 Distinguished Alumnus by the San Diego State University College 
of Sciences. 
</P>
<P>
Woodroof is widely recognized for his contributions in medical science. He 
developed two tissue heart valves and a wound dressing that is distributed 
worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
He graduated in 1966 with a degree in biology and received a doctorate in 
biochemistry from UCLA in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
Sandra Caton of Huntington Beach was named Woman of Achievement by the Orange 
County Chapter of Women in Management at its annual conference. A specialist in 
newsletters, she is a past president of the group and is owner of Caton 
Graphics and Publishing. 
</P>
<P>
Girl Scouts Vanessa Chepo of Huntington Beach and Stephanie Sumner of Mission 
Viejo have been chosen by their Girl Scout Council to attend the Capitol Event 
June 25-29 in Sacramento. The event teaches legislative process to the Scouts 
and prepares them for active roles in the political system. 
</P>
<P>
James A. Higgins of Laguna Beach, who has a 3.8 grade-point average at 
Saddleback College in Mission Viejo, has been named Outstanding Student at the 
community college level by the Orange County Engineering Council. 
</P>
<P>
It is the ninth time in 10 years that the award at the community college level 
has been won by a Saddleback College engineering student. 
</P>
<P>
Sandra K.Young of Newport Beach, a graduate of UCLA with a fine-arts degree, 
has been elected president of the 400-member Orange County chapter of the 
American Society of Interior Designers. 
</P>
<P>
Young is vice president of design and product development at the Levelor Corp., 
a manufacturer of window coverings. 
</P>
<P>
Members of her board of directors include Louise Bieger of Costa Mesa; Martha 
Burke of Fullerton; Lynn Deal of Newport Beach; Brian Freeborn of Long Beach; 
Christine Hallen-Berg and Jackie Jacobson, both of Laguna Beach; Roxanne 
Johnson of Orange; Jerry McKnight of Newport Beach; and Kent Roberts and Kathy 
Weir, both of Irvine. 
</P>
<P>
Boy Scout Eric Anderson, 17, of Yorba Linda will be awarded his Eagle Scout 
rank at a Court of Honor Sunday at St. Martin de Porres Church in Yorba Linda. 
</P>
<P>
Anderson painted safety marks and handball courts at Van Buren Elementary 
School in Yorba Linda. He attends Valencia High School. 
</P>
<P>
Santa Ana resident Helen Shanbrom has been named Woman of the Year in the 35th 
state Senate District by Sen. John Seymour (R-Anaheim). She was honored for her 
crusade to improve highway and truck safety. 
</P>
<P>
She became involved in truck safety four years ago after the death of her son 
due to a speeding truck. 
</P>
</TEXT>
